      <abstract id="aspace_825605610be1f7769112a22820c0bf14">Founded in 2001, the Commercial Closet Association, renamed AdRespect, began as a way to track and document lesbian, gay, bisexual, and transgender (LGBT) themed advertisements globally.  Michael Wilke, the founding executive director of the Commercial Closet Association, has researched and written about LGBT issues in advertising for over twenty years.  The collection is comprised of two series: print and media publications and photographs.  The print and media publications' series consists of mostly earmarked magazines and newspaper articles that were a part of Michael Wilke and the Commercial Closet Association's research ranging from 1975-2017. The photograph series is comprised of Wilke's personal photographs of family reunions, vacations and LGBT community events.</abstract>
      <physloc id="aspace_ea70938484bc4777ecf21e0066eb5685">Materials are stored offsite and advance notice is required for use. Please contact fales.library@nyu.edu at least two business days prior to your research visit to coordinate access.</physloc>
      <langmaterial id="aspace_6bd6f2c86bf5b2ef47c2166776687636">Materials primarily in English, with some publications in German and French.</langmaterial>
    </did>
    <scopecontent id="aspace_58aca3e5cd328c3886ff734f64bc8586">
      <head>Scope and Contents</head>
      <p>The collection documents the efforts of the Commercial Closet Association to collect and analyze domestic and international print and media advertisements that engage the LGBT community in positive and negative ways.  The collection is comprised of two series: print and media publications and photographs.  The print and media publications' series consists of mostly earmarked magazines and newspaper articles that were a part of Michael Wilke and the Commercial Closet Association's research ranging from 1975-2017. Major publications included within this series include <emph render="italic">Pride</emph>, <emph render="italic">Passport</emph>, <emph render="italic">Out</emph>, <emph render="italic">Outtraveler</emph>, <emph render="italic">Attitude</emph>, <emph render="italic">The Advocate</emph>, <emph render="italic">Genre</emph>, and <emph render="italic">The New York Times</emph>.  The photograph series is comprised of Wilke's personal photographs of family reunions, vacations and LGBT community events.</p>
    </scopecontent>
    <arrangement id="aspace_8961c9d54c6725b71d32000ab3dbe1e6">
      <head>Arrangement</head>
      <p>Organized into two series: Series I: Print and Media Publications; and Series II: Photographs. The materials in Series I are arranged chronologically and by publication title. The materials in Series II are arranged in the order in which they were received from the donor.</p>
    </arrangement>
    <bioghist id="aspace_1278c56f7baf574ecb4ae6017bf8a743">
      <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
      <p>Michael Wilke has researched and documented the marketing of lesbian, gay, bisexual, and transgender (LGBT) themed advertisements as a business journalist and nonprofit leader since 1992. Wilke is the founding executive director of the Commercial Closet Association, which began in New York City in May 2001. The Commercial Closet Association, now renamed AdRespect, continues its mission to promote "advertising that respects diversity, gender identity/expression, and sexual orientation for a more accepting society and better business results." Wilke studied journalism at the School of Visual Arts in New York City, and earned a masters of marketing at Zicklin Business School of Baruch College-City University of New York.  Previously, he worked as a business reporter at <emph render="italic">Advertising Age</emph> and has written about LGBT advertising and media for <emph render="italic">The New York Times</emph>, <emph render="italic">Adweek</emph>, <emph render="italic">Brandweek</emph>, <emph render="italic">The Advocate</emph>, <emph render="italic">Haymarket's Revolution</emph> marketing magazine, and <emph render="italic">Inside Media</emph>. He received the Gay and Lesbian Alliance Against Defamation (GLAAD) Media Award and was one of <emph render="italic">OUT</emph> magazine's OUT 100 in 2001.  Wilke has served as an advertising judge for the ANA Multicultural Excellence Awards, a Crain Lecturer at Northwestern University's Medill School of Journalism, and was a Hearst Professional in Residence fellowship at the University of Colorado at Boulder.</p>
    </bioghist>
